@node P7 "Getting on the Amiga Educator's List"
@toc "menu"

To get on the Amiga Educator's List send e-mail to
owl@davinci.reading.ma.us. Please specify whether you will be reading the
newsletter on Aminet or whether you would prefer to have it emailed to you.
The version on Aminet (found in the directory /docs/mags) runs with
AmigaGuide or Multiview which provides a spiffy hypertext presentation.
When requesting additions to the email list, please specify the uuencoded
or text version.  When no specification is made, we will assume that you
want the uuencoded lha file, which will allow you to view the hypertext
version.

@endnode

@node P8 "The Amiga Web Directory"
@toc "menu"
The Amiga Web Directory by @{"Lori Vinciguerra" link P6}

Most of you "Amiga web surfers" already know about one of the most valuable
and popular web sites, The Amiga Web Directory.  The Amiga Web Directory
was created and is maintained by the Champaign-Urbana Computer Users Group.
This page holds links to almost all of the intersting Amiga sites on the
web. To visit the directory go to the URL http://www.cucug.org/.

Here you will find a list of Amiga companies which is close to supreseding
AC's Guide to the Amiga.  To view the list of companies go to the URL
http://www.cucug.org/amicommercial.html. Although the companies are not
sorted by type of software, you may use the search function to look for
keyword, such as education.  While I was cruising here, I found several
sites which may be of interest to educators.

    Amiga Radiologist at http://www.portal.com/~mikety/ is a home page
    written by a licensed radiologist. The products on this page were
    announced in a previous issue of the AEL newsletter.

    FairBrothers at http://www.fairbrothers.com/ is a developer of
    foreign language educational software.

    Lascelles Productions at http://mail.inhb.co.nz/lascelles/ is a
    New Zealand company which makes educational software for the Amiga.
    Product titles include: Connosseur Fine Arts Collection, Nimble
    Numbers, Clockworks, SnoWords, Word Construction Set, Look! Hear!,
    Kim, and Back to Basics.

    Opportunity With Learning at http://pages.prodigy.com/ralph/owl.htm
    has the product "Physics Laboratory in Mechanics" which is on sale
    now if you visit the web site.

    Simon's Home Page at http://www.sjacobs.demon.co.uk/ has two pieces
    of mathematical software.  Graph creates cartesian and polar
    coordinate graphs.  Matrix allows you to solve for the determinant,
    the inverse, and solve linear equations.

All of these sites were easily found from the Amiga Web Directory.

Looking around the rest of the web, I found a couple of other sites which
I thought may be of interest to you educators.  Apparently, the U.S.
Department of Education is hosting a gopher site which includes freeware
and shareware for Amigans to download.  You can find this site at:

    gopher://gopher.ed.gov:70/00/software/Amiga

I also found a couple more commercial vendors with Amiga products:

    The Digital Universe is an astronomy package which has received rave
    reviews.  The home page for this site is
    http://www.syz.com/DU/amiga.html.

    Europress Software has a whole line of educational products. Some
    of these are available for the Amiga. Check out their site at
    http://www.europress.co.uk.

As more and more sites are being put up, the Web will become an invaluable
place to find educational resources. So everyone ... start surfing.

@endnode


